GLM: Project 0

Dina Iakovleva, Dmitry Donetskov, Elizaveta Chernenko, Ekaterina Korolkova

2019-01-05

Research Question

Are there region-specific differences in the Forced Vital Capacity (FVC) and the Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 second (FEV1)?

The dataset consists of

  • age, the age in years,
  • height, the height in cm,
  • weight, the weight in kg,
  • FVC, Forced Vital Capacity, the volume of air that can forcibly be blown out, after full inspiration, measured in centiliter,
  • FEV1, Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 second, the volume of air that can forcibly be blown out in first 1 second, after full inspiration, measured, in centiliter,
  • region, M - Murau (plenty of woods, no industries), A - Aichfeld (lots of industries).

Loading Data

The data is loaded into a data frame and the region variable is factorized.

data  <- read_excel("data/Spirometry.xlsx", sheet = "Tabelle1")

Building the pairwise comparision matrix which can help to understand the distribution of variables and their interaction with each other. All data in the plot is ‘groupped’ by the region.

p

The number of respondents are more or less even between the regions. The respondents are of different ages, height and weight from the regions so we can’t directly compare the estimaties of FVC, FEV1 between the regions without taking that difference into account.

It’s interesting to note few things

  • the ‘age’ input is not distributed normally, there are more young people,
  • the ‘height’, ‘weight’ inputs are not of a strong linear correlation, they are probably both required for the model,
  • there is a strong linear correlation between FVC and FEV1, so it might be enough to build a model for only either of them,
  • FVC is the right-skewed, FEV1 is of a bi-modal distribution; FVC may be a better response variable then as it can be easier linearized.

Let’s look closer at the relations of age, height and weight with FEV1, FVC because we are going to consider the linear regression based on that. Plotting the covariates against FEV1 and FVC.

gs <-list(NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA)

i <- 1
for (rv in c('FEV1', 'FVC')) {
  for (pv in c('age', 'height', 'weight')) {
    g <- ggplot(data = data, aes_string(x = pv, y = rv), alpha = 0.7) +
      geom_point(aes(color = region), size = 0.5) +
      geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y ~ x, color = 'green', se = FALSE) +
      geom_smooth()
    gs[[i]] <- g
    i <- i + 1
  }
}

pm <- ggmatrix(
  gs, nrow = 2, ncol = 3,

There is a considerable number of observations (n = 11) with the age less than 17 for the ‘A’ region. It can be an indicator of some error during the sampling. We should probably remove this subset of observations to make the data be more suitable for the linear regression. Alternatively, we can take the median value for that particular group and replace all the 11 cases with just one.

Let’s take the first approach: removing all those observations for the age equal 16. In doing that, we create a new dataset and store it in the data2 variable.

data2 <- data %>% filter(age > 16) %>% select(-year, -FEV1.VC)

Linear Regression

Tests for LM Assumptions

Linear relationship. The relationships between the covariates and either of FVC, FEV1 look to be more or less linear with some curves in the beginnig (judging by the ‘lowess’ line of the regression).

Normality. The age is not normally distributed. The Shapiro-Wilk normality test rejects the null hypothesis at the level p<0.003 for the whole dataset and it does not reject it for the reduced dataset (with the age more than 16) which can also justify that we removed those observations.

shapiro.test(data$age)

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  data$age
W = 0.94755, p-value = 0.002701
shapiro.test(data2$age)

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  data2$age
W = 0.96976, p-value = 0.09712

Variance. On the pairwise scatterplots each covariate has values around the regression line more or less evently.

Multicollinearity The Pearson’s correlation coeffiecient is not large for the pairs of the covariates. We will also try to diagnose violation of this assumption later while analysing the linear regression models.

Main Model

Let’s choose the model FVC ~ age + height because it has comparable R-squared and AIC with much more statistically significant intercept.

The diagnostic plot for it

autoplot(lm_FVC_2, which = 1:6, ncol = 3, label.size = 3, 
         title = sprintf('Diagnostic Plots for %s', as.character(formula(lm_FVC_2))), alpha = 0.7)

Box-Cox Transformation

Running the Box-Cox transformation for a range of lambda’s to find an optimal value.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

bc_runs_1 <- boxcox(lm_FVC_2,  lambda = seq(-1, 2, 0.01))
bc_lambda_FVC <- bc_runs_1$x[which.max(bc_runs_1$y)]
title(main = 'FVC ~ age + height',  sub = sprintf('max(lambda) = %.2f', bc_lambda_FVC),
      cex.main = 1)

bc_runs_2 <- boxcox(lm_FEV1_2, lambda = seq(-1, 2, 0.01))
bc_lambda_FEV1 <- bc_runs_2$x[which.max(bc_runs_2$y)]
title(main = 'FEV1 ~ age + height', sub = sprintf('max(lambda) = %.2f', bc_lambda_FEV1),
      cex.main = 1)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

The Box-Cox transformation suggests using \(\lambda=0.17\) for the FVC regression and \(\lambda=0.82\) for the FEV1 regression, these are the values when the MLE takes the maximum. Let’s build the models with the transformation.

The model for FEV1 with the Box-Cox transformation has got the statistically insignificant intercept, we stop considering it.

Conducting the test of significance of the optimal lambda’s value against the values of 0, 0.5, 1, 2 for FVC ~ age + height.

lm_FVC <- lm(data = data2, formula = FVC ~ age + height, model = FALSE)

# LME for the value of lambda when LME takes the maximum
bc_lme_FVC <- boxcox(lm_FVC, lambda = bc_lambda_FVC,  plotit = FALSE)$y

bc_runs = list(lambda = c(0, 0.5, 1, 2), y = rep(NA, 4))

i <- 1
for (lambda in bc_runs[['lambda']]) {
  bc <- boxcox(lm_FVC, lambda = lambda, plotit = FALSE)
  i <- i + 1
  lrt <- -2*(bc_lme_FVC - bc$y)
  print(sprintf('LRT Statistic for H0: boxcox(%.2f) = boxcox(%.2f): %.2f', lambda, bc_lambda_FVC, lrt))
  # Calculate the values based on the slide 42
  bc_runs[['y']][[i]] <- bc$y
}

Prediction

data_pred <- tibble(age = seq(17, 56))
data_pred['height'] <- 180
data_pred['weight'] <- 80
data_pred['region'] <- 'M'

data_pred['glm_FVC_gs_log'] <- predict.glm(glm_FVC_gs_log, newdata = data_pred, type = "response")
data_pred['glm_FVC_G_log']  <- predict.glm(glm_FVC_G_log,  newdata = data_pred, type = "response")

ggplot(data = data_pred, aes(x = age), alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_point(data = data2, aes(x = age, y = FVC)) +
  geom_line(data = data_pred, aes(x = age, y = glm_FVC_gs_log), color = 'red') + 
  geom_line(data = data_pred, aes(x = age, y = glm_FVC_G_log),  color = 'blue')

Ideas

  1. Regress on the volume of body rather than on just the height and/or the weight because the common sense suggests that the lung function depends on the volume of body rather than only on the latter two. A quick check on Google reveals there are works on calculating the volume using the two dimensions e.g. Sendroy Jr, Julius, and Harold A. Collison. “Determination of human body volume from height and weight.” Journal of Applied Physiology 21, no. 1 (1966): 167-172.
